Problems Found\\n\\nThe `Testing.MultipleTesting.Qvalues` module had **0% test coverage** despite providing critical functionality for multiple hypothesis testing:\\n- Q-value calculation from p-values (false discovery rate control)\\n- Pi0 estimation using Storey's bootstrap method\\n- Robust q-value calculation for small p-values\\n- Custom projection functions for flexible input types\\n\\n## Actions Taken\\n\\n### 1. Pi0 Bootstrap Estimation Tests (4 test cases)\\n- **Uniform p-values**: Tests behavior when p-values are uniformly distributed (pi0 should be high)\\n- **Mostly significant p-values**: Tests behavior with mostly small p-values (pi0 should be low)\\n- **Custom lambda values**: Tests `pi0BootstrapWithLambda` with user-specified lambda ranges\\n- **Deterministic behavior**: Validates that pi0 estimates are in valid range [0,1]\\n\\n### 2. Q-value Calculation with Projections (2 test cases)\\n- **ofPValuesBy**: Tests q-value calculation with custom projection (tuple extraction)\\n- **ofPValuesRobustBy**: Tests robust method with custom projection\\n- Validates that projection functions work correctly for structured data\\n\\n### 3. Edge Case and NaN Handling (5 test cases)\\n- **All NaN p-values**: Both `ofPValues` and `ofPValuesRobust` return NaN q-values\\n- **Mixed valid and NaN**: Validates correct handling of mixed input\\n- **Single p-value**: Tests minimum case scenario\\n- Ensures robust error handling and appropriate propagation of NaN values\\n\\n### 4. Mathematical Properties (5 test cases)\\n- **Monotonicity checks**: Q-values must be monotonic when sorted by p-values\\n- **pi0 boundary conditions**: Tests with pi0=1.0 (all nulls) and pi0=0.1 (few nulls)\\n- **Q-value vs P-value relationship**: Validates q-values \\u003e= p-values when appropriate\\n- **Valid range**: All q-values must be in [0, 1]\\n\\n## Test Coverage Results\\n\\n### Qvalues Module\\n| Metric | Before | After | Improvement |\\n|--------|--------|-------|-------------|\\n|