ts = \n   736â†’        ///     Interpolation.initInterpolate xData yData \n   737â†’        ///\n   738â†’        /// // get slope at 3.4\n   739â†’        /// Interpolation.differentiate coefficients 3.4 \n   740â†’        /// </code> \n   741â†’        /// </example>\n   742â†’        /// <remarks>X values that don't lie within the range of the input x values, are predicted using the nearest interpolation line!</remarks>\n   743â†’        let differentiate (lsc: StepCoef) x =\n   744â†’            0.\n   745â†’\n   746â†’\n   747â†’    /// <summary>\n   748â†’    ///   Module to create piecewise cubic polynomials (cubic subsplines) from x,y coordinates. \n   749â†’    ///   Akima subsplines are more flexible than standard cubic splines because the are NOT continuous in the function curvature, thereby diminishing oscillating behaviour.\n   750â†’    /// </summary>\n   751â†’    module Akima =\n   752â†’\n   753â†’        /// <summary>\n   754â†’        ///   Subsplines differ from regular splines because they are discontinuous in the second derivative.\n   755â†’        /// </summary>\n   756â†’        type SubSplineCoef = {\n   757â†’            /// sample points (N+1), sorted ascending\n   758â†’            XValues : float []\n   759â†’            /// Zero order spline coefficients (N)\n   760â†’            C0 : float []\n   761â†’            /// First order spline coefficients (N)\n   762â†’            C1 : float []\n   763â†’            /// Second order spline coefficients (N)\n   764â†’            C2 : float []\n   765â†’            /// Third order spline coefficients (N)\n   766â†’            C3 : float []\n   767â†’            } with \n   768â†’                static member Create xValues c0 c1 c2 c3 = {\n   769â†’                    XValues=xValues;C0=c0;C1=c1;C2=c2;C3=c3 \n   770â†’                    }\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code